AI Threat Addendum (ENISA-Aligned)
Credit Scoring System — Veriflow Payments Ltd

This is a thinking exercise. There is no such company.

Document type: Threat Addendum — AI System
Prepared by: Arken Systems GRC Function
Date: March 2025
Classification: Internal — Supporting Analysis

Primary reference: ENISA guidance on AI and cybersecurity risk

1. Purpose

This document highlights AI-specific threat considerations that are not fully addressed by standard control frameworks such as:

ISO/IEC 27001
NIST Cybersecurity Framework

It is intended as a supplement, not a replacement.

2. Framing Note

Traditional security controls assume:

Systems behave predictably
Inputs are either valid or malicious
Failures are visible

AI systems challenge all three assumptions.

3. Key AI-Specific Threat Scenarios
3.1 Data Poisoning (Upstream Manipulation)

Scenario
Training or enrichment data is subtly manipulated, altering model behaviour over time.

Relevance to Veriflow
Dependence on third-party enrichment data (Databridge) introduces indirect exposure.

Why this is difficult to detect

No obvious breach
Model performance may appear stable
Effects emerge gradually

This is less like an attack and more like a slow drift in reality.

3.2 Model Evasion (Adversarial Input)

Scenario
Applicants intentionally structure inputs to produce favourable outcomes.

Example
Manipulating income patterns or transaction characteristics to appear lower risk.

Why this matters

System appears accurate in aggregate
Individual exploitation becomes normalised

Controls tend to assume honest input.

That assumption does not always hold.

3.3 Model Inversion / Data Leakage

Scenario
Sensitive training data is inferred from model outputs.

Relevance
Lower likelihood in current deployment, but increases with model exposure (APIs, third-party access).

Control gap
Standard access controls do not fully mitigate inference risks.

3.4 Hidden Supply Chain Dependencies

Scenario
Third-party data or models introduce risk not visible at the contractual level.

Example
Databridge relying on additional undisclosed data sources.

Why this matters

Risk is inherited, not owned
Assurance stops at the first supplier layer

This is already visible in traditional supply chains.
AI makes it harder to trace.

3.5 Behavioural Manipulation (Non-Technical)

Scenario
Users adapt behaviour in response to perceived model logic.

Example
Customers changing transaction behaviour to influence scoring.

Observation
This is not strictly malicious.

But it still changes system integrity over time.

4. Control Implications

These risks do not require entirely new frameworks.

They require different questions to be asked within existing ones:

Not just “Is the data secure?”
→ “Could the data be shaping the model in unintended ways?”
Not just “Is access controlled?”
→ “Could outputs reveal more than intended?”
Not just “Is the supplier compliant?”
→ “What are they indirectly introducing into the system?”
5. Final Observation

These threats rarely appear as clear incidents.

They appear as:

Gradual shifts
Edge-case failures
Patterns that only make sense in hindsight

Which means they are easy to miss.

And difficult to explain once they surface.
